defaultWritten evidence submitted by Christine Ann Wellington [WAS0024]default&#xa0;defaultIntroductiondefaultThe benefits of regularly participating in sport are known and unequivocal. Heath benefits are both physical (eg cardio-vascular endurance, co-ordination, flexibility, weight management) and psychological (enjoyment, anti-depressant, self-esteem). Transferable skills - time management, organisation, goal setting, 
defaultteamwork
default – are also of considerable value. Sport builds bridges and unites communities. Increasing participation is an investment in the overall economic, cultural and social health of our nation.
defaultEquity is expected by the public and enshrined in law. It is therefore entirely reasonable to suggest that similar opportunities should exist for women to participate in, succeed at and make a living from sport as they do for men. 
defaultIt must be remembered that ‘women/girls’ is not a homogenous category and consideration must be given to differences in income level, age, ethnicity, place of residence and disability.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis submission considers the barriers to participation, and makes recommendations for overcoming them, at the grassroots and elite level.  Action requires genuine, transparent and honest collaboration between all stakeholders
default. 
defaultGrassroots Level: Barriers and Recommendations for ActiondefaultBarriers to participation at the grassroots can be grouped into: financial, practical, personal/psychological and institutional.  
